docs.lead_paragraph:
KAPLAN--Tobee. The board and professionals of Hillel International send our heartfelt condolences to the family of our dear friend Tobee Kaplan z'l. Tobee was a visionary who loved Hillel dearly and made it a passion with her late husband, Leonard z'l. They served with distinction on Hillel's Board of Governors and were honored with Hillel's Renaissance Award in 2009. Our condolences are with her son Randall Kaplan, former Chair of Hillel International's Board of Governors and Board of Directors, his wife Kathy Manning and the entire Kaplan family. May they be comforted among the mourners of Zion and Jerusalem.

David Shapira, Chair of Board of Governors; Tina Price, Chair of Board of Directors; Eric D. Fingerhut, Pres/CEO, Hillel Intl

docs.lead_paragraph:
SCHULMAN--Jerome L.,

M.D., died at home in New York on June 30. He was 89. Dr. Schulman, a pioneering virologist in influenza research, was on the faculty of the Mount Sinai School of Medicine from 1968 until he retired in 2005. He was one of the first to discover the uniqueness of the Hong Kong virus of 1968 by differentiating it from previously prevalent Asian viruses. The Hong Kong strain had killed an estimated one million people worldwide. Surviving is his wife of 56 years, the poet Grace Schulman.

docs.lead_paragraph:
DWORKIN--Albert R.,

passed away in his home in Sarasota, Florida on July 17, three days before his 100th birthday. He was born of immigrant parents in Newark, NJ, where he graduated from Weequahic High School. Bright and ambitious, he graduated from the NYU School of Commerce while working during the day for his father and later graduated from the Fordham Law School. A member of the New York bar, he became a CPA, tax attorney, and partner with the New York accounting firm of David Berdon & Co. He and his beloved wife of 73 years, Phyllis, lived for many years in Roslyn, Long Island until their retirement to Sarasota 30 years ago. He was predeceased earlier this year by Phyllis and by a son, Eric. A wonderful father and grandfather, he is survived by daughter Peggy Northrop of Barrington, Rhode Island, son Peter Dworkin of San Francisco, five grandchildren, and two great-granddaughters. May the memory of the righteous be a blessing.
